ut there are also a great many excellent and inspirational ones who instil the very love of learning you mention. Love for life probably does depend more on background, I admit, but I very much doubt that this is limited to children who don't go to school. &#10;It seems your daughter had a bad time at school, and I'm sorry to hear it. But this is not the experience of most state school children I know (including my own). &#10;You didn't respond to most of the points in my previous post, so I suppose it's not worth my making any further ones. &#10;Maybe it's time for you to calm down, go to bed, and eat the Daily Mail."/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="916" language="en" documentId="986" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="yixing" date="07 November 2009 1:33am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6751237" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="1" thumbsDown="0" origId="986" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="127"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="128" end="560"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="561" end="724"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="725" end="843"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="844" end="916"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55"/></xmi:XMI>